		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">No true Scotsman</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">For the practice of wearing a kilt without undergarments, see <a href="/wiki/True_Scotsman" title="True Scotsman">True Scotsman</a>.</div>
<p><b>No true Scotsman</b>, or the <b>self-sealing fallacy</b>, is a <a href="/wiki/Logical_fallacy" title="Logical fallacy" class="mw-redirect">logical fallacy</a> where the meaning of a term is <a href="/wiki/Ad_hoc" title="Ad hoc">ad hoc</a> <a href="/wiki/Fallacy_of_equivocation" title="Fallacy of equivocation" class="mw-redirect">redefined</a> to <a href="/wiki/Begging_the_question" title="Begging the question">tautologically</a> make a desired assertion about it true.</p>
<p>It was advanced by philosopher <a href="/wiki/Antony_Flew" title="Antony Flew">Antony Flew</a> in his 1975 book <i>Thinking About Thinking – or do I sincerely want to be right?</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
<tr>
<td>
<div id="toctitle">
<h2>Contents</h2>
</div>
<ul>
